The framework built around this trait is split into three components: the analysis runtime, the analysis engine, and the local analysis engine. At the highest level, the analysis runtime is responsible for handling invocations of analysis passes and caching results. As the data-ﬂow trait prevents implementers from holding state, the analysis runtime can cache results on a per-type basis. This cache is used to make the point at which analyses are run transparent. That is, whenever a piece of code requires the results of an analysis pass, it asks the analysis runtime as if it were for the ﬁrst time. If the analysis results have not yet been generated, the runtime spins up an analysis engine to compute them, otherwise, the cached results are returned immediately. A concrete illustration is given in ﬁgure 3.10.
